fields.description:
Register user with fields defined in the settings.

If the email field of the user model is part of the
registration fields (default), check if there is
no user with that email or as a secondary email.

If it exists, it does not register the user,
even if the email field is not defined as unique
(default of the default django user model).

When creating the user, it also creates a `UserStatus`
related to that user, making it possible to track
if the user is archived, verified and has a secondary
email.

Send account verification email.

If allowed to not verified users login, return token.
fields.name: register

fields.description:
Verify user account.

Receive the token that was sent by email.
If the token is valid, make the user verified
by making the `user.status.verified` field true.
fields.name: verifyAccount

fields.description:
Sends activation email.

It is called resend because theoretically
the first activation email was sent when
the user registered.

If there is no user with the requested email,
a successful response is returned.
fields.name: resendActivationEmail

fields.description:
Send password reset email.

For non verified users, send an activation
email instead.

Accepts both primary and secondary email.

If there is no user with the requested email,
a successful response is returned.
fields.name: sendPasswordResetEmail

fields.description:
Change user password without old password.

Receive the token that was sent by email.

If token and new passwords are valid, update
user password and in case of using refresh
tokens, revoke all of them.
fields.name: passwordReset

fields.description:
Change account password when user knows the old password.

A new token and refresh token are sent. User must be verified.
fields.name: passwordChange

fields.description:
Archive account and revoke refresh tokens.

User must be verified and confirm password.
fields.name: archiveAccount

fields.description:
Delete account permanently or make `user.is_active=False`.

The behavior is defined on settings.
Anyway user refresh tokens are revoked.

User must be verified and confirm password.
fields.name: deleteAccount

fields.description:
Update user model fields, defined on settings.

User must be verified.
fields.name: updateAccount

fields.description:
Send activation to secondary email.

User must be verified and confirm password.
fields.name: sendSecondaryEmailActivation

fields.description:
Verify user secondary email.

Receive the token that was sent by email.
User is already verified when using this mutation.

If the token is valid, add the secondary email
to `user.status.secondary_email` field.

Note that until the secondary email is verified,
it has not been saved anywhere beyond the token,
so it can still be used to create a new account.
After being verified, it will no longer be available.
fields.name: verifySecondaryEmail

fields.description:
Swap between primary and secondary emails.

Require password confirmation.
fields.name: swapEmails

fields.description:
Obtain JSON web token for given user.

Allow to perform login with different fields,
and secondary email if set. The fields are
defined on settings.

Not verified users can login by default. This
can be changes on settings.

If user is archived, make it unarchive and
return `unarchiving=True` on output.
fields.name: tokenAuth

fields.description: Same as `grapgql_jwt` implementation, with standard output.
fields.name: verifyToken

fields.description: Same as `grapgql_jwt` implementation, with standard output.
fields.name: refreshToken

fields.description: Same as `grapgql_jwt` implementation, with standard output.
fields.name: revokeToken

types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.
fields.name: types

fields.name: queryType

fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.
fields.name: mutationType

fields.name: subscriptionType

types.name: __Schema

types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByURL`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.
types.name: __Type

types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.
enumValues.name: SCALAR

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.
enumValues.name: OBJECT

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.
enumValues.name: INTERFACE

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.
enumValues.name: UNION

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.
enumValues.name: ENUM

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.
enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.
enumValues.name: LIST

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.
enumValues.name: NON_NULL

types.name: __TypeKind

types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.
types.name: __Field

types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.
fields.name: defaultValue

types.name: __InputValue

types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.
types.name: __EnumValue

types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.
types.name: __Directive
